**Content:** While online education is relatively young compared to traditional universities, the latter’s economic model is struggling.  Online platforms allow for cost-effective scaling. Creating a high-quality online course has a high initial cost, but the repeated use drastically reduces the per-student cost compared to traditional models where costs are continually reinvested for every course offering.
**Argument:** Traditional universities' economic models are struggling. Online platforms allow for cost-effective scaling. High initial cost of online course creation is offset by repeated use, reducing per-student cost. Traditional models require continual reinvestment for every course offering.

**Claim:** Online platforms empower teachers by providing resources and freeing up time for valuable interactions.
**Purpose:** reinforce => Blended learning models demonstrate the transformative power of online components.;
**Content:** Furthermore, online platforms can empower teachers.  Educators can leverage existing online resources to enhance their in-person classes, particularly in underserved communities. Technology, like automated essay grading, can free up teachers' time for more valuable interactions. While high-level education benefits from expert feedback, this technology allows more students to benefit from frequent writing practice, something currently limited by teachers’ time constraints.
**Argument:** Educators can leverage online resources to enhance in-person classes, especially in underserved communities. Technology like automated essay grading frees up teachers' time. This allows more students to benefit from frequent writing practice, which is currently limited by teachers' time constraints.

